\section{Related Work}

\textbf{Physical AI safety.} Safety shielding intercepts agent actions against formal specifications before execution~\cite{alshiekh2018safe}. Conformal prediction bounds agent confidence to prevent dangerous overreach~\cite{angelopoulos2021conformal}. Recent advances in embodied foundation models (e.g., PaLM-E~\cite{driess2023palme}, RT-2~\cite{brohan2023rt2}) have brought LLM reasoning directly into physical environments, amplifying the need for grounded action verification. Our clinical guardrail follows this shielding pattern. Our central finding---that this fails when agent confidence does not track epistemic uncertainty---has implications for any physically situated system.

\textbf{LLM-based clinical agents.} AgentClinic~\cite{schmidgall2025agentclinic} demonstrated that structured multi-agent workflows improve diagnostic accuracy. MDAgents~\cite{kim2024mdagents} and MEDDxAgent~\cite{rose2025meddxagent} showed further gains through adaptive collaboration. Our prior Med-Guard system~\cite{jain2024medguard} introduced dedicated safety agents. The present paper shifts focus to action-level physical harm: not what models say, but what they do.

\textbf{Clinical AI safety evaluation.} MedSafetyBench~\cite{han2024medsafety} and red-teaming work~\cite{balazadeh2025redteam} evaluate whether models refuse to produce harmful text. MedSentry~\cite{chen2025medsentry} taxonomises conversational failure modes. These primarily evaluate output-level safety rather than downstream action-level risk. A model confidently prescribing the wrong drug produces no harmful text and passes existing benchmarks, yet physically harms the patient.

\textbf{Confidence calibration.} Neural networks are notoriously overconfident~\cite{guo2017calibration}, and LLMs degrade in calibration near competence boundaries~\cite{kadavath2022know}. Our results (ECE 0.246--0.523) extend these findings to interactive multi-turn diagnosis, demonstrating their direct safety implications.

