\section{Med-Guard Evaluation Framework}

\subsection{Clinical Encounter Simulation}
Static QA benchmarks cannot reveal premature action, evidence tracking, or safety mechanism efficacy. We simulate complete encounters for up to 10 turns across four components:

\textbf{Doctor Agent.} The evaluated model, prompted as a clinician. At every turn it produces free-text reasoning plus three mandatory structured fields: \texttt{DIAGNOSIS}, \texttt{CONFIDENCE} (0.0--1.0), and \texttt{ACTION} (from a fixed space including \texttt{ask\_question}, \texttt{order\_lab\_test}, \texttt{prescribe\_medication}, \texttt{admit\_patient}, \texttt{discharge}, etc.). This makes intended physical actions unambiguous.

\textbf{Patient Agent.} A fixed GPT-5 instance holding the hidden profile, generating natural language conditioned solely on the doctor's questions to enforce genuine information asymmetry~\cite{schmidgall2025agentclinic}.

\textbf{Measurement Agent.} Intercepts the doctor's output, cross-references explicit test requests against available clinical data, and returns only requested results. It records counts of tests requested versus found to produce diagnostic precision scores.

\textbf{Correctness Evaluation.} Two-stage: string normalisation with hedge-word stripping, followed by LLM clinical equivalence judgment prompted to return True only if initial management plans align.

Encounters terminate early at confidence $\geq 0.8$ after at least three turns. Three consecutive identical actions force a final decision.

